25 /*
26 Standalone program to read a MySQL binary log (or relay log).
27
28 Should be able to read any file of these categories, even with
29 --start-position.
30 An important fact: the Format_desc event of the log is at most the 3rd event
31 of the log; if it is the 3rd then there is this combination:
32 Format_desc_of_slave, Rotate_of_master, Format_desc_of_master.
33 */

1190 /**
1191 Print auxiliary statements ending a binary log (or a logical binary log
1192 within a sequence of relay logs; see below).
1193
1194 There are two kinds of log files which can be printed by mysqlbinlog
1195 binlog file - generated by mysql server when binlog is ON.
1196 relaylog file - generated by slave IO thread. It just stores binlog
1197 replicated from master with an extra header(FD event,
1198 Previous_gtid_log_event) and a tail(rotate event).
1199 when printing the events in relay logs, the purpose is to print
1200 the events generated by master, but not slave.
1201
1202 There are three types of FD events:
1203 - Slave FD event: has F_RELAY_LOG set and end_log_pos > 0
1204 - Real master FD event: has F_RELAY_LOG cleared and end_log_pos > 0
1205 - Fake master FD event: has F_RELAY_LOG cleared and end_log_pos == 0
1206
1207 (Two remarks:
1208
1209 - The server_id of a slave FD event is the slave's server_id, and
1210 the server_id of a master FD event (real or fake) is the
1211 master's server_id. But this does not help to distinguish the
1212 types in case replicate-same-server-id is enabled. So to
1213 determine the type of event we need to check the F_RELAY_LOG
1214 flag.
1215
1216 - A fake master FD event may be generated by master's dump
1217 thread (then it takes the first event of the binlog and sets
1218 end_log_pos=0), or by the slave (then it takes the last known
1219 real FD event and sets end_log_pos=0.) There is no way to
1220 distinguish master-generated fake master FD events from
1221 slave-generated fake master FD events.
1222 )
1223
1224 There are 8 cases where we rotate a relay log:
1225
1226 R1. After FLUSH [RELAY] LOGS
1227 R2. When mysqld receives SIGHUP
1228 R3. When relay log size grows too big
1229 R4. Immediately after START SLAVE
1230 R5. When slave IO thread reconnects without user doing
1231 START SLAVE/STOP SLAVE
1232 R6. When master dump thread starts a new binlog
1233 R7. CHANGE MASTER which deletes all relay logs
1234 R8. RESET SLAVE
1235
1236 (Remark: CHANGE MASTER which does not delete any relay log,
1237 does not cause any rotation at all.)
1238
1239 The 8 cases generate the three types of FD events as follows:
1240 - In all cases, a slave FD event is generated.
1241 - In cases R1 and R2, if the slave has been connected
1242 previously, the slave client thread that issues
1243 FLUSH (or the thread that handles the SIGHUP) generates a
1244 fake master FD event. If the slave has not been connected
1245 previously, there is no master FD event.
1246 - In case R3, the slave IO thread generates a fake master FD
1247 event.
1248 - In cases R4 and R5, if AUTOPOSITION=0 and MASTER_LOG_POS>4,
1249 the master dump thread generates a fake master FD event.
1250 - In cases R4 and R5, if AUTOPOSITION=1 or MASTER_LOG_POS<=4,
1251 the master dump thread generates a real master FD event.
1252 - In case R6, the master dump thread generates a real master FD
1253 event.
1254 - In cases R7 and R8, the slave does not generate any master FD
1255 event.
1256
1257 We define the term 'logical binlog' as a sequence of events in
1258 relay logs, such that a single logical binlog may span multiple
1259 relay log files, and any two logical binlogs are separated by a
1260 real master FD event.
1261
1262 A transaction's events will never be divided into two binlog files or
1263 two logical binlogs. But a transaction may span multiple relay logs, in which
1264 case a faked FD will appear in the middle of the transaction. they may be
1265 divided by fake master FD event and/or slave FD events.
1266
1267 * Example 1
1268
1269 relay-log.1
1270 ...
1271 GTID_NEXT=1
1272 BEGIN;
1273
1274 relay-log.2
1275 ...
1276 faked Format_description_event
1277 INSERT ...
1278 COMMIT;
1279
1280 For above case, it has only one logical binlog. The events
1281 in both relay-log.1 and relay-log.2 belong to the same logical binlog.
1282
1283 * Example 2
1284
1285 relay-log.1
1286 ...
1287 GTID_NEXT=1
1288 BEGIN; // It is a partial transaction at the end of logical binlog
1289
1290 relay-log.2
1291 ...
1292 real Format_description_event
1293 GTID_NEXT=1
1294 BEGIN;
1295 ...
1296
1297 For above case, it has two logical binlogs. Events in relay-log.1
1298 and relay-log.2 belong to two different logical binlog.
1299
1300 Logical binlog is handled in a similar way as a binlog file. At the end of a
1301 binlog file, at the end of a logical binlog or at the end of mysqlbinlog it
1302 should
1303 - rollback the last transaction if it is not complete
1304 - rollback the last gtid if the last event is a gtid_log_event
1305 - set gtid_next to AUTOMATIC
1306
1307 This function is called two places:
1308 - Before printing a real Format_description_log_event(excluding the
1309 first Format_description_log_event), while mysqlbinlog is in the middle
1310 of printing all log files(binlog or relaylog).
1311 - At the end of mysqlbinlog, just after printing all log files(binlog or
1312 relaylog).
